Defendant Garret M Vandierendonck in court with attorney Christopher J Ertl.  Intern Ian Vance-Curzan under the supervision of Jesica A Ballenger appeared for Benjamin Lindsay for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

AS TO COUNT 1:  The defendant was advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by the state, defense, and defendant. 

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served with credit for 0 days served.  The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 18 MONTHS.  The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program.

The Court orders this sentence STAYED and the defendant is placed on probation for 3 YEARS with the following conditions:

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Corrections with release privileges for employment and the day reporting center (programming/vocational training). NO ELECTRONIC MONITORING ALLOWED;
*Obtain Mental health assessment- complete follow-up treatment;
*Take any and all prescribed medication only in the manner/dosage as prescribed by treating physician;
*Obtain AODA assessment- complete follow-up treatment;
*Absolute sobriety, no drugs or alcohol with random urine screens and breathalyzer tests;
*No illegal drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers/houses);
*Cooperate with all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment, if enrolled in school full time, part time work;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample if not done so- pay surcharge;
*No driving without valid license;  

The Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $600 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, including $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge by the end of the probation period.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment. Court ordered AODA assessment and Driver's Safety Plan.  Court ordered defendant's driving privileges revoked for a period of 3 years.  Court ordered defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an ignition interlock device for 3 years.   If revoked, the Court ordered that all financial obligations be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.  Appeal rights given by the court.
